State MSM Profile: Oklahoma

Background & Methods

In 2015-2016, researchers at Emory University partnered with colleagues at the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC) to develop methods to estimate the number of men who have sex with men (MSM) residing in each county in the United States. Using population and housing data from the American Community Survey and estimates from two peer-reviewed publications (Oster et al., 2015 & Purcell et al., 2012), they derived an indirect estimate of MSM population sizes that took into account both the urbanicity of the county as well as its density of households with a male householder and a male same-sex partner.

The full methodology is published in the Journal of Medical Internet Research - Public Health and Surveillance:

Grey JA, Bernstein KT, Sullivan PS, Purcell DW, Chesson HW, Gift TL, Rosenberg ES. Estimating the population sizes of men who have sex with men in US states and counties using data from the American Community Survey. JMIR Public Health Surveill 2016;2(1):e14. DOI: 10.2196/publichealth.5365

Overview of MSM in Oklahoma

An estimated 37,738 men who have sex with men (MSM) resided in Oklahoma in 2013, representing 0.8% of the 4,503,084 MSM in the United States. Of the 1,394,881 adult men of Oklahoma, 2.7% had had sex with another man in the past 5 years, which was less than the overall percentage of adult men in the United States who were MSM (3.9%).

Most MSM in Oklahoma resided in central counties of large metropolitan areas (37.2%). Including both central and fringe counties, 55.5% resided in a large metropolitan area.


Percentage of MSM by urbanicity, United States and Oklahoma, 2013

MSM in Oklahoma Counties

Among counties or county-equivalent areas in Oklahoma, Oklahoma County had the largest population of MSM at 14,027, representing 37.2% of all MSM in the state. Oklahoma County also had the highest percentage of MSM among adult men in Oklahoma at 5.3%. This was greater than the percentage for Oklahoma as a whole, which was 2.7% of adult men.

Note: Range cutpoints for the map are based on the distribution of MSM among all counties in the United States.



MSM in Oklahoma Metropolitan Statistical Areas

Oklahoma City Metropolitan Statistical Area

The Oklahoma City MSA had the largest metropolitan population of MSM in Oklahoma at 20,929, or 55.5% of all MSM in the state. Of the 466,055 adult men in Oklahoma City, an estimated 4.5% were MSM.

Note: Range cutpoints for the map are based on the distribution of MSM among all counties in the United States.




Tulsa Metropolitan Statistical Area

The Tulsa MSA had a population of 7,560 MSM, or 20.0% of all MSM in Oklahoma. Of the 341,185 adult men in Tulsa, an estimated 2.2% were MSM.

Note: Range cutpoints for the map are based on the distribution of MSM among all counties in the United States.




Lawton Metropolitan Statistical Area

The Lawton MSA had a population of 962 MSM, or 2.5% of all MSM in Oklahoma. Of the 50,925 adult men in Lawton, an estimated 1.9% were MSM.

Note: Range cutpoints for the map are based on the distribution of MSM among all counties in the United States.




Fort Smith Metropolitan Statistical Area

The Fort Smith MSA overlaps two states: Arkansas and Oklahoma. The Oklahoma portion of the MSA had 767 MSM, or 2.0% of all MSM in the state and 33.2% of the 2,310 MSM in the MSA. Of 34,087 adult men in the Oklahoma part of Fort Smith, 2.3% were MSM. This was equal to the overall percentage of MSM among adult men in the MSA, which was 2.3% of adult men (2,310 out of 102,040).

Note: Range cutpoints for the map are based on the distribution of MSM among all counties in the United States.
